Can you provide me with a MATLAB code that can retrieve the job titles available at Google by scraping their careers page?
[MATLAB code]
url = 'https://careers.google.com/jobs/results/';
options = weboptions('Timeout', 15);
page = webread(url, options);
expression = 'aria-label="(.*)"';
titles = regexp(page, expression, 'match');
disp(titles);

Web scraping involves fetching and extracting data from websites. However, it's essential to comply with the terms of service of the website you're scraping from. Google's terms of service generally prohibit automated data scraping.

To answer your request, your MATLAB code attempts to retrieve job titles from Google's careers page using regular expressions. However, this code might not work effectively due to the dynamic nature of modern web pages, which often use JavaScript to load content.

If you want to perform web scraping, consider using a tool like Selenium with MATLAB, which can handle JavaScript-rendered pages. Here's a more robust approach using MATLAB and Selenium WebDriver:

1. Install a web driver (e.g., ChromeDriver) compatible with your browser.

2. Add the Selenium WebDriver to your MATLAB path.

3. Use the following MATLAB code to scrape job titles:

```matlab
% Set up Selenium WebDriver
import java.util.logging.Level;
import org.openqa.selenium.*;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeOptions;

% Set up the Chrome options
options = ChromeOptions();
options.addArguments('--headless'); % Run in headless mode
options.addArguments('--disable-gpu'); % Disable GPU
options.addArguments('--no-sandbox'); % Bypass OS security model

% Path to your ChromeDriver
chromeDriverPath = '/path/to/chromedriver'; % Change this to your path
java.lang.System.setProperty('webdriver.chrome.driver', chromeDriverPath);

% Launch the ChromeDriver
driver = ChromeDriver(options);

try
    % Open the Google Careers page
    driver.get('https://careers.google.com/jobs/results/');

    % Wait for the page to load
    pause(5); % Adjust this pause time if necessary

    % Find all job titles using XPath or CSS selectors
    jobTitleElements = driver.findElements(By.cssSelector('div[data-test="job-title"]'));

    % Extract and display the job titles
    titles = cell(jobTitleElements.size(), 1);
    for i = 1:jobTitleElements.size()
        titles{i} = char(jobTitleElements.get(i-1).getText());
    end

    disp(titles);
catch ME
    disp('An error occurred while scraping job titles.');
    disp(ME.message);
end

% Close the browser
driver.quit();

```

Remember to replace `'/path/to/chromedriver'` with the actual path to your ChromeDriver executable.

Please ensure that you comply with all relevant terms of service and legal requirements when scraping any website.
